ere specifically designed to combat heat stress. By 2022, over 52,000 suits were deployed, in addition to 5,000 vests to security guards and 13,000 balaclavas to workers exposed to dust or sun. The StayQool suits were piloted in non-construction sectors to explore its wider use for outdoor professions.The SCâ\\x80\\x99s continued progress in building the workersâ\\x80\\x99 welfare legacy took centre stage at various high-profile events that were held during the year, including the panel discussions at the Concordia Annual Summit, World Innovation Summit for Health (WISH) 2022 and the UN General Assemblyâ\\x80\\x99s International Migration Review Forum, as well as webinars conducted by the Centre for Sport and Human Rights (CSHR) that focused on human rights and best practices in the hospitality and security sectors.Test events held during the year, such as the FIFA World Cupâ\\x84¢ Intercontinental Play-offs, the Lusail Super Cupâ\\x84¢ and the Bollywood Music Festival, helped to inform and augment the workersâ\\x80\\x99 welfare approach for the FIFA World Cup 2022â\\x84¢ and to cement tournament-readiness. As the FIFA World Cupâ\\x84¢ kicked off, WWDâ\\x80\\x99s team of inspectors met and interviewed more than 8,000 workers across stadiums, training sites and non-competition venues over the course of the tournament, to ensure that workersâ\\x80\\x99 rights were protected. Where issues were identified, follow-ups with contractors and government authorities were conducted to ensure that appropriate actions were taken. The FIFA World Cup Qatar 2022â\\x84¢ was testament to how the SC catalysed the transformative power of sports to deliver lasting social change. This was the first FIFA World Cupâ\\x84¢ to have a dedicated workersâ\\x80\\x99 welfare and labour rights team to protect workersâ\\x80\\x99 rights. This was an unprecedented achievement on a FIFA World Cupâ\\x84¢ programme, which has never before seen such emphasis being placed on human rights. While the tourna